<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="202" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="9.[2050,2642,531,958]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2050,2206,531,564]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Shortridge &amp;" box="[2225,2641,531,564]" class="Cryptophyceae" family="Cryptomonadaceae" genus="Cryptochloris" kingdom="Chromista" order="Cryptomonadales" pageId="9" pageNumber="202" phylum="Cryptista" rank="species" species="zyli">Cryptochloris zyli Shortridge &amp;</taxonomicName>
Carter, 1938, 
<materialsCitation pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Compagnies Drift, 16 km inland from Lamberts Bay, Western Cape Province, South Africa.</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[2050,2642,531,958]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">
The species 
<taxonomicName box="[2235,2276,693,722]" class="Cryptophyceae" family="Cryptomonadaceae" genus="Cryptochloris" kingdom="Chromista" order="Cryptomonadales" pageId="9" pageNumber="202" phylum="Cryptista" rank="species" species="zyli">zyli</taxonomicName>
was formerly considered subspecifically distinct from C. 
<taxonomicName box="[2491,2587,732,761]" class="Mammalia" family="Chrysochloridae" genus="Chrysochloris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="9" pageNumber="202" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wintoni">wintoni</taxonomicName>
but now considered a distinct species due to consistent differences in pelage color and malleus morphology. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="202" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6624548" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6624548" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6624548/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="202" targetBox="[1435,2026,542,956]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph blockId="9.[2050,2642,531,958]" lastBlockId="9.[1436,2642,968,1746]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2050,2226,886,919]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Distribution.</emphasis>
Endemic to W South Africa, being found at two sites (Groenriviermond in Northern Cape Province and Lamberts Bay in Western Cape Province); possibly ranges N along coast to Olifants River.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="202" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[1436,2642,968,1746]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1438,1687,1043,1076]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 82 mm, hindfoot 12 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Based on only three specimens, Van Zyl’s Golden Mole is very small, with short, dark lead-gray dorsal pelage; venter is similar but drab. Course guard hairs have violet metallic sheen, giving pelage sparkly appearance.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="202" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[1436,2642,968,1746]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1438,1549,1200,1233]" pageId="9" pageNumber="202">Habitat.</emphasis>
Uncertain, but expected to occur in coastal dune belt and possibly sandy areas of Strandveld Succulent Karoo biome of the Namaqua coastal plain.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
